data.content:
## Migration Analysis

### APIs that must change

| API | Line | Why it breaks on .NET 8 |
|-----|------|------------------------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9); unreliable way to wake `WaitOne` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+ |

### Patterns identified

| Pattern | Location | Replacement strategy |
|---------|----------|---------------------|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (true)` in `RunLoop` | Check `CancellationToken` in loop condition |
| **Blocking call interruption** | `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` |
| **Timeout + forced kill** | `Join(5000)` → `Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` — cooperative stop replaces the forced kill entirely |

### Pre-existing race condition (tightly coupled — fixing it)

The original code has a bug: if `Enqueue` is called twice before `RunLoop` wakes, `Reset()` clears the signal after dequeuing only one item — the second item is stuck until the next enqueue. The migrated version drains the queue properly.

---

### Migrated code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        try
        {
            // GetConsumingEnumerable blocks until an item is available
            // and throws OperationCanceledException when the token is cancelled.
            foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(_cts.Token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Normal shutdown — nothing to do.
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _queue.Add(item);
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _queue.CompleteAdding();   // signals no more items
        _cts.Cancel();            // wakes thread if blocked in GetConsumingEnumerable
        _thread?.Join(5000);      // wait for graceful exit — no Abort needed
    }

    private void Handle(string item)
    {
        // existing processing logic
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Dispose();
        _queue.Dispose();
    }
}
```

---

### What changed and why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|------------------------|----------------|-----|
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` | `BlockingCollection<string>` | Thread-safe producer/consumer with built-in blocking — eliminates the manual signal/lock/queue coordination and the race condition |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` | Cooperatively wakes the blocked `GetConsumingEnumerable` call |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Removed entirely | Not needed — `Cancel()` ensures the loop exits, so `Join(5000)` succeeds |
| `while (true)` + `WaitOne/Reset/Dequeue` | `foreach (... GetConsumingEnumerable(...))` | Single call replaces 4 lines; handles all edge cases (empty queue, multiple items, cancellation) |
| No `IDisposable` | `IDisposable` added | `CancellationTokenSource` and `BlockingCollection` must be disposed to avoid timer/handle leaks |

### Key pitfalls to watch for

1. **`CancellationToken` doesn't interrupt `Handle(item)`** — if `Handle` does long-running work, pass `_cts.Token` into it and check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at safe points. Otherwise the thread won't stop until the current item finishes.

2. **Don't call `Enqueue` after `Stop`** — `CompleteAdding()` marks the collection as closed. Calling `Add` afterward throws `InvalidOperationException`. Guard with `_queue.IsAddingCompleted` if callers may race with shutdown.

3. **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** — leaking it causes timer and callback leaks. The `IDisposable` pattern ensures cleanup.

4. **`Join(5000)` can still time out** — but unlike the original code, there's no `Abort()` fallback. If `Handle` is truly stuck, the thread will leak. For uncooperative code, move work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill`.
